com.esri.mo2.util
Class Resource

java.lang.Object
  |
  +--com.esri.mo2.util.Resource
public class Resource
extends Object

Simple-to-use access methods for Class resources that are stored within a JAR. Use the getImage method to load an image from a JAR, or getProperties to load a Properties set.

This class also provides keyed access to ResourceBundles. You can use the getBundleText method to obtain simpe text as might be used with a menu name. Use formatMessage method to construct a complex message using text from the ResourceBundle and parameters that you supply. Several helper methods are available for quickly constructing a message with zero, one or two parameters.

getImage

public static Image getImage(Class c,
                             String r)
                      throws IOException
Returns an Image that is associated with a particular class. This method is a wrapper for the Class.getResourceAsStream() method, which is the only Netscape-supported technique for obtaining class resources.

This method will invoke getImage(Class,int) using a default image size "hint".

the image

public static Image getImage(Class c,
                             String r,
                             int h)
                      throws IOException
Returns an Image that is associated with a particular class. Calling code provides a strong hint regarding the size of the image. Preferably, the "hint" is a number of bytes that is larger than the actual image size, but getImage() will still work if the specified number turns out to be smaller. In that case, getImage() has to work to get the image data in chunks.

getIcon

public static Image getIcon(Class resClass,
                            String r)
Returns an icon image from the resource JAR. The resource name specified can either contain a complete package path begins with a "/") in which case it will be obtained from that path, or it can be specified relative to the location of a Resource file in which case it will be obtained from an look-and-feel based path or the standard default path.

dir
 |
 |- AResFile.java
 |- ico
 |    |- anIcon.gif
 |    |- anotherIcon.gif
 |
 |- laf
 |    |- lookAndFeelName
 |        |- ico
 |            |- anIcon.gif
 |            |- anotherIcon.gif

The user can place Look-and-feel based icons. For example to use the open.gif, for different look-and-feels, the user can create icons and place them in an appropriate directory. For example, When the user calls getIcon(com.esri.mo2.res.Res.class, "tb/open.gif") :
For Metal look-and-feel (javax.swing.plaf.metal.MetalLookAndFeel), com/esri/mo2/res/laf/metal/ico/tb/open.gif
For Aqua look and feel (apple.laf.AquaLookAndFeel), com/esri/mo2/res/laf/aqua/ico/tb/open.gif
For Windows look and feel (com.sun.java.swing.plaf.windows.WindowsLookAndFeel), com/esri/mo2/res/laf/windows/ico/tb/open.gif
For Motif look and feel (com.sun.java.swing.plaf.motif.MotifLookandFeel), com/esri/mo2/res/laf/motif/ico/tb/open.gif
For XXX look and feel (foo.lookFeel.someclass.XXXLookAndFeel), com/esri/mo2/res/laf/xxx/ico/tb/open.gif
If an icon is not found in the location based on look-and-feel, an icon from the default location (in this case) com/esri/mo2/res/ico/tb/open.gif is returned.

Parameters:
resClass - class relative to which icons are to be searched.
r - absolute path to resource
Returns:
look-and-feel based icon or '/com/esri/mo2/res/ico/cmn/broken.gif' if no icon found.

getBundleArray

public static String[] getBundleArray(String key,
                                      String separator)
Returns an array of text values from the ResourceBundle for the given key and text separator. The resource text indicated by the key is assumed to consist of one or more values delimited by the separator. For example if the value contains "hello|world" and the separator is "|" then the text array returned will be {"hello","world"}

Parameters:
key - the resource bundle key
separator - the value separator
Returns:
the array of values found, null if no key, empty array if key is present but no text

formatMessage

public static String formatMessage(String key,
                                   Object[] params)
An utility for obtaining and formatting a localized message including specified parameters. The pattern used for formatting the message is obtained from the default MapObjects--Java messages ResourceBundle using the specified key, then java.text.MessageFormat is used to apply the formatting.

Parameters:
key - the key into the default ResourceBundle
params - the parameters to be formatted with the message
Returns:
the formatted string, or an Exception text if any error was encountered
See Also:
formatMessage(String,String,Object[])

formatMessage

public static String formatMessage(String bundleLocation,
                                   String key,
                                   Object[] params)
An utility for obtaining and formatting a localized message including specified parameters. The pattern used for formatting the message is obtained from the ResourceBundle specified by the bundle location, and using the specified key. java.text.MessageFormat is used to apply the formatting.

Parameters:
bundleLocation - resource bundle location, as package path name
key - the key into the default ResourceBundle
params - the parameters to be formatted with the message
Returns:
the formatted string, or an Exception text if any error was encountered
